critique: This executive order suspends a previous order that brought certain positions into the competitive classified civil service. It establishes a committee to study personnel practices. The order seems to grant some discretion to the Civil Service Commission in determining which positions are suitable for competitive examination. It's difficult to assess a strong ideological tilt without more context, but it seems to be related to the efficiency and management of the civil service. Immigration is not addressed. The order delegates authority to a committee and the Civil Service Commission, so it's hard to say if it expands executive power. It doesn't seem to have a strong impact on federalism. It's difficult to assess its impact on national security vs. civil liberties. It seems to have a moderate impact on economic regulation by affecting the civil service. It doesn't seem to have a strong impact on social inclusion.
